\section{Introduction}
% ---------------------------------------------------
% Write introduction here
% ---------------------------------------------------
\noindent Time series analysis is widely used to extract features from observational data in applications such as prediction and anomaly detection. Recently, nonlinearities in astronomical data have gained attention for their role in understanding the generation of strong X-rays from AGN \cite{ref1}. However, such nonlinear characteristics are difficult to capture with linear methods and are often misinterpreted as noise. 

To analyze one-dimensional data sequences, nonlinear time series analysis is a new method that can extract nonlinear dynamics from the data. Its application to astronomical flux variability, which inherently exhibits nonlinearity and nonstationarity, is particularly effective. 

In this study, we apply a recurrence plot, a method of nonlinear time-series analysis, to one-dimensional gamma-ray data from blazars to explore the dynamical structures underlying their variability. We also assess how preprocessing procedures, such as linear interpolation, affect these dynamical characteristics. As a result, one-dimensional data sequences with linear interpolation tend to show increased laminarity, likely because interpolation introduces artificial temporal continuity. This tendency is observed both in blazar data and in benchmark dynamical systems.

\section{Recurrence Plot (RP) and Recurrence Quantification analysis (RQA)}
% ---------------------------------------------------
% Write related work here
% ---------------------------------------------------
\noindent In this study, to elucidate the dynamical structure embedded in an observed one-dimensional sequence, the phase space is reconstructed based on Takens' embedding theorem. To evaluate the recurrence structure of the state on the reconstructed attractor, RP and RQA are applied.

\section{Recurrence Plot}
% ---------------------------------------------------
% Write device description here
% ---------------------------------------------------
\noindent The recurrence plot is defined by the recurrence matrix. The matrix defined as Eq. (2) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
  R_{i,j} = \Theta(\varepsilon - ||x_i - x_j||),
\end{equation}
where $x_i$ and $x_j$ denote points on the reconstructed attractor in phase space $i,j=1,\ldots N$. $\varepsilon$ is the threshold, and $\Theta$ indicates the Heaviside step function. The element $R_{i,j} = 1$ indicates that two points $x_i$ and $x_j$ are sufficiently close by threshold epsilon. $R_{ij}=1$ denotes on the plot as a black dot, whereas $R_{i,j} = 0$ is shown as a white dot. By plotting this binary matrix on a two-dimensional index space, the recurrence plot visualizes recurrence patterns and reveals nonlinear and nonstationary structures in a one-dimensional sequence. The recurrence plot is an N × N plane, where N corresponds to the total number of  points on the attractor.  

\section{Recurrence quantification analysis (RQA)}
% ---------------------------------------------------
% Write results here
% ---------------------------------------------------
\noindent RQA provides a quantitative framework for evaluating the recurrence structures observed qualitatively in recurrence plots. By measuring the geometric patterns that reflect the system’s temporal behavior, RQA enables objective assessment of dynamical properties in one-dimensional data.

The RQA measures used in this study are summarized in Table 1.
\begin{table}[h]
  \centering
  \small
  \caption{Definitions of RQA measures}
  
  \begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}
  {|>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{0.38\columnwidth}|X|}
  \hline
  Recurrence Rate (RR) & Overall proportion of recurrent state \\ \hline
  Determinism (DET) & Degree to which recurrent points form deterministic diagonal patterns \\ \hline
  Diagonal ratio (DEratio) & Relative dominance of diagonal (deterministic) structure \\ \hline
  Average diagonal line length (L) & Average duration of predictable behavior \\ \hline
  Diagonal line entropy (EN) & Complexity of diagonal line length distribution \\ \hline
  Laminarity (LAM) & Proportion of laminar (vertical) structure \\ \hline
  Trapping time (TT) & Average duration of laminar states \\ \hline
  \end{tabularx}
\end{table}


\section{Result and Disscution}
\subsection{Time-Series Structure and Recurrence Plot (RP)}
\noindent Figure 1 shows a blazar gamma-ray time series after linear interpolation (upper figure) and its recurrence plot (lower figure). In the upper panel of Fig. 1, the blue points represent the observed data, and the red solid line corresponds to the linear interpolation function. Missing values were filled using linear interpolation, and the resulting interpolated data points are shown as red markers. RP exhibits characteristic structures reflecting the temporal evolution of the reconstructed dynamics in the lower figure.

From Fig. 1, a pronounced block-like structure appears around 200–300 weeks, highlighted by the blue circle. This region corresponds to a segment reconstructed by linear interpolation, and the dense horizontal and vertical lines within it indicate artificially enhanced laminarity caused by increased temporal continuity. Similar patterns occur across the dataset, suggesting that linear interpolation systematically inflates laminarity-related RQA measures and affects their interrelationships.
\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{time_R.P_abstruct.png}
    \caption{Gamma-ray flux (upper) and its RP (lower) for 1ES2322-409.}
    \label{time-linear}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Validation Using Known Dynamical Systems}
\noindent Figure 2 summarizes how linear interpolation affects laminarity-related RQA measures across eight benchmark dynamical systems, including the Lorenz attractor, logistic map, sine wave, Brownian motion, white noise, and their noise-added variants. Missing values were introduced at rates from 0\% to 90\% and reconstructed using linear interpolation. Recurrence plots were then generated from the interpolated sequences, and the mean laminarity (mLAM) was evaluated. 

Figure 2 demonstrates that the effect of missing data on mLAM depends strongly on the step-to-step variability of the underlying dynamics. Systems with large variability, such as white noise and the logistic map, show a sharp and systematic rise in mLAM as the missing rate increases because linear interpolation imposes artificial temporal continuity on originally stochastic or discontinuous sequences. In contrast, intrinsically smooth and continuous systems, including the sine wave and the Lorenz attractor, maintain stable laminarity with minimal changes in mLAM, indicating that interpolation has little impact on their recurrence structure.
\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.77\linewidth]{trend_mLAM.png}
    \caption{Effect of Linear Interpolation on Laminarity in Known Dynamical Systems}
    \label{8rqa}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Correlation Between Laminarity(LAM) and Trapping Time(TT)}
LAM and TT quantify the frequency and duration of vertical structures in RP, making their joint behavior informative about temporal persistence in the reconstructed dynamics. As shown in Fig.3, TT increases markedly only when LAM becomes high, revealing a clear positive correlation. This indicates that prolonged trapping occurs mainly in strongly laminar regions, suggesting that the LAM-TT relationship can serve as a diagnostic for interpolation-induced artifacts.
\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.78\linewidth]{lam_vs_tt.png}
    \caption{Relationship Between LAM and TT Across the Dataset}
    \label{8rqa}
\end{figure}


\section{Conclusion}
\noindent This study applied RP and RQA to blazar gamma-ray data, finding that linear interpolation systematically inflates laminarity-related measures. This highlights that preprocessing significantly influences the dynamical interpretation of astronomical time series.
Therefore, careful assessment of interpolation effects is essential when characterizing the dynamical properties of one-dimensional astronomical sequences.


